'''Kotohira Ōtori Shrine''' (金刀比羅・大鷲神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Magane Town|ja|真金町|12=draft}}, {{ill|Minami-ku (Yokohama)|ja|南区 (横浜市)|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yokohama|ja|横浜市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kanagawa Prefecture|ja|神奈川県|12=draft}}. It is a former {{ill|Unranked Shrine|ja|無格社|12=draft}}. The registered name as a religious corporation is '''Religious Corporation Kotohira Shrine''' (宗教法人金刀比羅神社). The shrine grounds also include a subordinate shrine dedicated to {{ill|Fushimi Inari Shrine|ja|伏見稲荷神社|12=draft}}.

== Deities ==
* Kotohira Shrine
** {{ill|Ōmononushi|ja|大物主命|1=Ōmononushi|lt=Ōmononushi-no-Mikoto|12=draft}} ([[Konpira Gongen]])
** {{ill|Emperor Sutoku|ja|崇徳天皇|12=draft}}
* Ōtori Shrine
** {{Interlanguage link multi|Ame-no-torifune|ja|鳥之石楠船神|vertical-align=sup}}

== History ==
; Kotohira Shrine
In {{ill|1859|ja|1859th year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Ansei 6|ja|安政6th year|12=draft}}), with the opening of {{ill|Yokohama Port|ja|横浜港|12=draft}}, the proprietor of the Iwakame Rō brothel in the {{ill|Minatozaki Yūkaku|ja|港崎遊郭|12=draft}}, Sakichi of Iwatsukiya, enshrined the {{ill|Zōzu-san Konpira Daigongen|ja|象頭山 金毘羅大権現|12=draft}} from {{ill|Sanuki Province|ja|讃岐国|12=draft}}. The shrine was initially established in the {{ill|Minatozaki Town|ja|港崎町|12=draft}} area (the current site of {{ill|Yokohama Park|ja|横浜公園|12=draft}}).<br>
In {{ill|1872|ja|1872nd year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Meiji 5|ja|明治5th year|12=draft}}), along with the relocation of the {{ill|Yūkaku|ja|遊廓|12=draft}}, the shrine was moved to the coastal area of Takashima Town 7-chōme and renamed Kotohira Shrine. In {{ill|1882|ja|1882nd year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Meiji 15|ja|明治15th year|12=draft}}), it was relocated again to {{ill|Magane Town|ja|真金町|12=draft}} for the same reasons.<br>
The shrine was damaged during both the {{ill|1923 Great Kantō Earthquake|ja|関東大震災|12=draft}} on September 1, {{ill|1923|ja|1923rd year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Taishō 12|ja|大正12nd year|12=draft}}) and the {{ill|Yokohama Air Raid|ja|横浜大空襲|12=draft}} on May 29, {{ill|1945|ja|1945th year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Shōwa 20|ja|昭和20th year|12=draft}}). Although it was rebuilt each time, the current main shrine building was reconstructed in {{ill|1988|ja|1988th year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Shōwa 63|ja|昭和63rd year|12=draft}}).

; Ōtori Shrine
In {{ill|1872|ja|1872nd year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Meiji 5|ja|明治5th year|12=draft}}), when the {{ill|Minatozaki Yūkaku|ja|港崎遊郭|12=draft}} was moved to Takashima Town, a deity known as the "Otorisama" was enshrined following the example of {{ill|Yoshiwara Yūkaku|ja|吉原|12=draft}} in {{ill|Tokyo|ja|東京|12=draft}}.<ref>It is unclear whether this refers to {{ill|Ōtori Shrine (Taitō)|ja|鷲神社 (台東区)|1=Ōtori Shrine (Taito Ward)|lt=Ōtori Shrine|12=draft}} in Asakusa, Tokyo, or {{ill|Ōtori Shrine (Adachi)|ja|大鷲神社 (足立区)|12=draft}} in Hanahata, Adachi, Tokyo.</ref> From this time, the {{ill|Tori no Ichi|ja|酉の市|1=Tori-no-Ichi|12=draft}} festival was held, similar to Asakusa. Initially, it was a subordinate shrine within the grounds, but it is now enshrined alongside Kotohira Shrine.

== location ==
* 1-3 Magane Town, Minami-ku, Yokohama, Kanagawa Prefecture, Japan

