In {{ill|1872|ja|1872nd year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Meiji 5|ja|明治5th year|qq=draft}}), along with the relocation of the {{ill|Yūkaku|ja|遊廓|qq=draft}}, the shrine was moved to the coastal area of Takashima Town 7-chōme and renamed Kotohira Shrine. In {{ill|1882|ja|1882nd year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Meiji 15|ja|明治15th year|qq=draft}}), it was relocated again to {{ill|Magane Town|ja|真金町|qq=draft}} for the same reasons.<br>
The shrine was damaged during both the {{ill|1923 Great Kantō Earthquake|ja|関東大震災|qq=draft}} on September 1, {{ill|1923|ja|1923rd year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Taishō 12|ja|大正12nd year|qq=draft}}) and the {{ill|Yokohama Air Raid|ja|横浜大空襲|qq=draft}} on May 29, {{ill|1945|ja|1945th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Shōwa 20|ja|昭和20th year|qq=draft}}). Although it was rebuilt each time, the current main shrine building was reconstructed in {{ill|1988|ja|1988th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Shōwa 63|ja|昭和63rd year|qq=draft}}).

; Ōtori Shrine
In {{ill|1872|ja|1872nd year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Meiji 5|ja|明治5th year|qq=draft}}), when the {{ill|Minatozaki Yūkaku|ja|港崎遊郭|qq=draft}} was moved to Takashima Town, a deity known as the "Otorisama" was enshrined following the example of {{ill|Yoshiwara Yūkaku|ja|吉原|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Tokyo|ja|東京|qq=draft}}.<ref>It is unclear whether this refers to {{ill|Ōtori Shrine (Taitō)|ja|鷲神社 (台東区)|1=Ōtori Shrine (Taito Ward)|lt=Ōtori Shrine|qq=draft}} in Asakusa, Tokyo, or {{ill|Ōtori Shrine (Adachi)|ja|大鷲神社 (足立区)|qq=draft}} in Hanahata, Adachi, Tokyo.</ref> From this time, the {{ill|Tori no Ichi|ja|酉の市|1=Tori-no-Ichi|qq=draft}} festival was held, similar to Asakusa. Initially, it was a subordinate shrine within the grounds, but it is now enshrined alongside Kotohira Shrine.

