[[ja:金刀比羅・大鷲神社]]

== History ==
; Kotohira Shrine
In {{ill|1859|ja|1859年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1859|qq=}} ({{ill|Ansei 6|ja|安政6年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ansei 6|qq=}}), with the opening of {{ill|Yokohama Port|ja|横浜港|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yokohama Port|qq=}}, the proprietor of the Iwakame Rō brothel in the {{ill|Minatozaki Yūkaku|ja|港崎遊郭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minatozaki Yūkaku|qq=}}, Sakichi of Iwatsukiya, enshrined the {{ill|Zōzu-san Konpira Daigongen|ja|象頭山 金毘羅大権現|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zōzu-san Konpira Daigongen|qq=}} from {{ill|Sanuki Province|ja|讃岐国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sanuki Province|qq=}}. The shrine was initially established in the {{ill|Minatozaki Town|ja|港崎町|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minatozaki Town|qq=}} area (the current site of {{ill|Yokohama Park|ja|横浜公園|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yokohama Park|qq=}}).<br>
In {{ill|1872|ja|1872nd year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1872|qq=}} ({{ill|Meiji 5|ja|明治5年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji 5|qq=}}), along with the relocation of the {{ill|Yūkaku|ja|遊廓|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yūkaku|qq=}}, the shrine was moved to the coastal area of Takashima Town 7-chōme and renamed Kotohira Shrine. In {{ill|1882|ja|1882nd year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1882|qq=}} ({{ill|Meiji 15|ja|明治15年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji 15|qq=}}), it was relocated again to {{ill|Magane Town|ja|真金町|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Magane Town|qq=}} for the same reasons.<br>
The shrine was damaged during both the {{ill|1923 Great Kantō Earthquake|ja|関東大震災|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1923 Great Kantō Earthquake|qq=}} on September 1, {{ill|1923|ja|1923年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1923|qq=}} ({{ill|Taishō 12|ja|大正12nd year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taishō 12|qq=}}) and the {{ill|Yokohama Air Raid|ja|横浜大空襲|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yokohama Air Raid|qq=}} on May 29, {{ill|1945|ja|1945年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1945|qq=}} ({{ill|Shōwa 20|ja|昭和20年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōwa 20|qq=}}). Although it was rebuilt each time, the current main shrine building was reconstructed in {{ill|1988|ja|1988年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1988|qq=}} ({{ill|Shōwa 63|ja|昭和63年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōwa 63|qq=}}).

; Ōtori Shrine
In {{ill|1872|ja|1872nd year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1872|qq=}} ({{ill|Meiji 5|ja|明治5年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji 5|qq=}}), when the {{ill|Minatozaki Yūkaku|ja|港崎遊郭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minatozaki Yūkaku|qq=}} was moved to Takashima Town, a deity known as the "Otorisama" was enshrined following the example of {{ill|Yoshiwara Yūkaku|ja|吉原|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshiwara Yūkaku|qq=}} in {{ill|Tokyo|ja|東京|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokyo|qq=}}.<ref>It is unclear whether this refers to {{ill|Ōtori Shrine (Taitō)|ja|鷲神社 (台東区)|1=Ōtori Shrine (Taito Ward)|lt=Ōtori Shrine|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtori Shrine (Taitō)|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtori Shrine (Taito Ward)|qq=}} in Asakusa, Tokyo, or {{ill|Ōtori Shrine (Adachi Ward)|lt=Ōtori Shrine (Adachi Ward)|lt=Ōtori Shrine (Adachi)|ja|大鷲神社 (足立区)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtori Shrine (Adachi)|qq=}} in Hanahata, Adachi, Tokyo.</ref> From this time, the {{ill|Tori no Ichi|ja|酉の市|1=Tori-no-Ichi|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tori no Ichi|13=User:Immanuelle/Tori-no-Ichi|qq=}} festival was held, similar to Asakusa. Initially, it was a subordinate shrine within the grounds, but it is now enshrined alongside Kotohira Shrine.

== location ==
* 1-3 Magane Town, Minami-ku, Yokohama, Kanagawa Prefecture, Japan

