== History ==
; Kotohira Shrine
In [[:en:1859|1859]] ({{ill|Ansei 6|ja|安政6年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ansei 6|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}), with the opening of [[:en:Port of Yokohama|Yokohama Port]], the proprietor of the Iwakame Rō brothel in the {{ill|Minatozaki Yūkaku|ja|港崎遊郭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minatozaki Yūkaku|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 港崎遊廓|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 港崎遊廓|1=Miyozaki Quarter|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11563079}}, Sakichi of Iwatsukiya, enshrined the {{ill|Zōzu-san Konpira Daigongen|ja|象頭山 金毘羅大権現|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zōzu-san Konpira Daigongen|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} from [[:en:Sanuki Province|Sanuki Province]]. The shrine was initially established in the {{ill|Minatozaki Town|ja|港崎町|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minatozaki Town|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} area (the current site of {{ill|Yokohama Park|ja|横浜公園|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yokohama Park|qq=|1=Yokohama Park|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11542924}}).<br>
In [[:en:1872|1872]] ([[:en:1872|Meiji 5]]), along with the relocation of the [[:en:Yūkaku|Yūkaku]], the shrine was moved to the coastal area of Takashima Town 7-chōme and renamed Kotohira Shrine. In [[:en:1882|1882]] ([[:en:1882|Meiji 15]]), it was relocated again to {{ill|Magane Town|ja|真金町|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Magane Town|qq=|1=Maganechō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11583588}} for the same reasons.<br>
The shrine was damaged during both the {{ill|1923 Great Kantō Earthquake|ja|関東大震災|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1923 Great Kantō Earthquake|qq=|1=aftermath of 1923 Great Kantō earthquake|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q3742341}} on September 1, [[:en:1923|1923]] ([[:en:1923|Taisho 11]]) and the {{ill|Yokohama Air Raid|ja|横浜大空襲|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yokohama Air Raid|qq=|1=Bombing of Yokohama|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11542960}} on May 29, [[:en:1945|1945]] ([[:en:1945|Showa 20]]). Although it was rebuilt each time, the current main shrine building was reconstructed in [[:en:1988|1988]] ([[:en:1988|Showa 63]]).

; Ōtori Shrine
In [[:en:1872|1872]] ([[:en:1872|Meiji 5]]), when the {{ill|Minatozaki Yūkaku|ja|港崎遊郭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minatozaki Yūkaku|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 港崎遊廓|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 港崎遊廓|1=Miyozaki Quarter|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11563079}} was moved to Takashima Town, a deity known as the "Otorisama" was enshrined following the example of {{ill|Yoshiwara Yūkaku|ja|吉原|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshiwara Yūkaku|qq=|1=Yoshihara|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q4053786}} in {{ill|Tokyo|ja|東京|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokyo|qq=|1=Tokyo|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q7473516}}.<ref>It is unclear whether this refers to {{ill|Ōtori Shrine (Taitō)|ja|鷲神社 (台東区)|1=Ōtori Shrine (Taito Ward)|lt=Ōtori Shrine|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtori Shrine (Taitō)|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtori Shrine (Taito Ward)|qq=}} in Asakusa, Tokyo, or {{ill|Ōtori Shrine (Adachi Ward)|lt=Ōtori Shrine (Adachi Ward)|lt=Ōtori Shrine (Adachi)|ja|大鷲神社 (足立区)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtori Shrine (Adachi)|qq=}} in Hanahata, Adachi, Tokyo.</ref> From this time, the {{ill|Tori no Ichi|ja|酉の市|1=Tori-no-Ichi|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tori no Ichi|13=User:Immanuelle/Tori-no-Ichi|qq=}} festival was held, similar to Asakusa. Initially, it was a subordinate shrine within the grounds, but it is now enshrined alongside Kotohira Shrine.

